markdown <<MARKDOWN
# Conditionals   


#### Let's examine what is happening in the code from the previous level.

<img src="https://images.code.org/f3ef1f77da436feb6031a01556611ba8-image-1741629200115.png" alt="code with conditional and painter painting blue" width="550px" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">

#### When the computer reaches line 11 and sees the `if` statement, it checks whether the painter can move south. If the answer is yes, the painter will paint the square blue and then move south.

#### This `if` statement appears twice in the code. The first time it runs—when the painter is in the top-right corner—it can move south, so it moves and paints. 

#### The second time, on line 15, the painter checks again, but this time a truck is blocking the way. Since it cannot move south, the condition is false, and the painter skips that part of the code.

## Conditional Statements

#### A **conditional statement** is a command that runs only if a certain condition is true, allowing a program to make decisions. 

<img src="https://images.code.org/0a3045036a3ec53ae086f14a6eeb2704-image-1741629741213.png" alt="code with a conditional underlined" width="400px" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">

--- 

## Syntax for Conditional Statements


<div style="background-color: #F7F8FA; color: #000000; padding: 15px; border-radius: 10px; width: 90%; margin: 20px auto; box-shadow: 4px 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2); display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between;">
  
  <div style="flex: 1;">
    <p style="font-size: 14pt; font-weight: bold; margin: 0;">Coding a Conditional</p><br>
